{"title_page": "Vanni Treves", "text_new": "{{short description|British television executive}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n'''Vanni Emanuele Treves''' [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (1940 &ndash; 10 November 2019)<ref>[http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/deaths/237263/treves Treves]</ref> was a British business executive. He was Chairman of [[Channel 4]] (1998\u20132003), a senior partner of [[City of London|City]] law firm [[Macfarlanes]], and Chairman (2001\u20132009)<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.equitable.co.uk/content/pressreleases_archive.asp?frm_yr=2009\n|title = Press Release Archive 2009\n|accessdate = 2009-12-18\n|year = 2009\n|work = [[The Equitable Life Assurance Society|Equitable Life]]\n|publisher = [[The Equitable Life Assurance Society|Equitable Life]]\n}}</ref> of [[The Equitable Life Assurance Society|Equitable Life]].<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.equitable.co.uk/content/content_8.htm\n|title = The Board\n|accessdate = 2009-12-18\n|year = 2009\n|work = [[The Equitable Life Assurance Society|Equitable Life]]\n|publisher = [[The Equitable Life Assurance Society|Equitable Life]]\n}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nTreves was born in [[Florence]], Italy in 1940.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/movers_and_shakers/executive_movers/article4636075.ece|title=Vanni Treves: the barrister manqu\u00e9 at Korn/Ferry|date=30 August 2008|work=Martin Waller|publisher=[[The Times]]|accessdate=2008-09-21}}</ref>  His father was killed during the [[Second World War]] in 1944 and his mother remarried, hence the family relocated to [[Swiss Cottage]] in London. He won a scholarship to the independent [[St Paul's School (London)|St Paul's School]], London before attending the [[University of Oxford]] to study [[jurisprudence]]. Treves later completed a [[Fulbright scholarship]] in the United States at the [[University of Illinois]]. He relinquished his dual Italian-British nationality at the age of 36 when he realised that it made him eligible for [[national service]] in the [[Italian Army]].<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/may/09/voluntarysector.childprotection\n|title = Corporate charmer coaxing cash for children's charity\n|accessdate = 2008-09-21\n|date = 9 May 2008\n|work = Philip Inman\n|publisher = [[The Guardian]]\n}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFollowing his graduation from Oxford, Treves joined Macfarlanes in 1963 and went on to become a specialist in corporate governance. It was this that led to his appointment as a non-executive director of [[Saatchi & Saatchi]] in 1987. During the 1990s he went on to develop a career, as Philip Inman puts it, as a \"serial chairman.\" In 2001 he took up the chairmanship of [[The Equitable Life Assurance Society|Equitable Life]], determined to resolve its troubles.<ref name=\"The Guardian\"/>\n\nTreves was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the 2012 New Year Honours for services to education (as chair of the [[National College for School Leadership]]).<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60009 |date=31 December 2011 |page=8 |supp=y }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTreves was married with two sons and a daughter.<ref name=\"The Guardian\"/> He was a donor to the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].<ref>http://www.thelawyer.com/equitable-boss-shown-to-be-new-labour-donor/101221.article</ref>\n\nHe authored \"What life after retirement from the law?\" which was published in ''The Times'' on 4 April 2013.<ref>http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/law/article3729351.ece</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box|title=Chairman of [[Channel 4]]|before=[[Michael Bishop (businessman)|Michael Bishop]]|after=[[Luke Johnson (businessman)|Luke Johnson]]|years=January 1998 \u2013 December 2003}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Treves, Vanni}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British solicitors]]\n[[Category:British television executives]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Fulbright Scholars]]\n[[Category:Italian emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children people]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Paul's School, London]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign alumni]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) donors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British television executive}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n'''Vanni Emanuele Treves''' [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (1940 &ndash; 10 November 2019)<ref>[http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/deaths/237263/treves Treves]</ref> was a British business executive. He was Chairman of [[Channel 4]] (1998\u20132003), a senior partner of [[City of London|City]] law firm [[Macfarlanes]], and Chairman (2001\u20132009)<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.equitable.co.uk/content/pressreleases_archive.asp?frm_yr=2009\n|title = Press Release Archive 2009\n|accessdate = 2009-12-18\n|year = 2009\n|work = [[The Equitable Life Assurance Society|Equitable Life]]\n|publisher = [[The Equitable Life Assurance Society|Equitable Life]]\n}}</ref> of [[The Equitable Life Assurance Society|Equitable Life]].<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.equitable.co.uk/content/content_8.htm\n|title = The Board\n|accessdate = 2009-12-18\n|year = 2009\n|work = [[The Equitable Life Assurance Society|Equitable Life]]\n|publisher = [[The Equitable Life Assurance Society|Equitable Life]]\n}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nTreves was born in [[Florence]], Italy in 1940.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/movers_and_shakers/executive_movers/article4636075.ece|title=Vanni Treves: the barrister manqu\u00e9 at Korn/Ferry|date=30 August 2008|work=Martin Waller|publisher=[[The Times]]|accessdate=2008-09-21}}</ref>  His father was killed during the [[Second World War]] in 1944 and his mother remarried, hence the family relocated to [[Swiss Cottage]] in London. He won a scholarship to the independent [[St Paul's School (London)|St Paul's School]], London before attending the [[University of Oxford]] to study [[jurisprudence]]. Treves later completed a [[Fulbright scholarship]] in the United States at the [[University of Illinois]]. He relinquished his dual Italian-British nationality at the age of 36 when he realised that it made him eligible for [[national service]] in the [[Italian Army]].<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/may/09/voluntarysector.childprotection\n|title = Corporate charmer coaxing cash for children's charity\n|accessdate = 2008-09-21\n|date = 9 May 2008\n|work = Philip Inman\n|publisher = [[The Guardian]]\n}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFollowing his graduation from Oxford, Treves joined Macfarlanes in 1963 and went on to become a specialist in corporate governance. It was this that led to his appointment as a non-executive director of [[Saatchi & Saatchi]] in 1987. During the 1990s he went on to develop a career, as Philip Inman puts it, as a \"serial chairman.\" In 2001 he took up the chairmanship of [[The Equitable Life Assurance Society|Equitable Life]], determined to resolve its troubles.<ref name=\"The Guardian\"/>\n\nTreves was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the 2012 New Year Honours for services to education (as chair of the [[National College for School Leadership]]).<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60009 |date=31 December 2011 |page=8 |supp=y }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTreves was married with two sons and a daughter.<ref name=\"The Guardian\"/> He was a donor to the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].<ref>http://www.thelawyer.com/equitable-boss-shown-to-be-new-labour-donor/101221.article</ref>\n\nHe authored \"What life after retirement from the law?\" which was published in ''The Times'' on 4 April 2013.<ref>http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/law/article3729351.ece</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box|title=Chairman of [[Channel 4]]|before=[[Michael Bishop (businessman)|Michael Bishop]]|after=[[Luke Johnson (businessman)|Luke Johnson]]|years=January 1998 \u2013 December 2003}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Treves, Vanni}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British solicitors]]\n[[Category:British television executives]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Fulbright Scholars]]\n[[Category:Italian emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children people]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Paul's School, London]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign alumni]]\n", "name_user": "HonkyDory64", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Labour Party donor)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vanni_Treves"}
